<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Here, Las Casas can be seen to present to the Crown the terrible demographic collapse of the indigenous populations in the New World. His reference to the 30 other islands around San Juan (Puerto Rico) make clear the complexity of native society, and the spread of destruction as wrought by the effects of colonization. More notable perhaps, is his insistence not only in their depopulation, but in their destruction. Although he makes no specific reference to violence, and although disease was the greatest killer of native Americans, Las Casas can be seen here to infer that human agency was responsible for the destruction of native society on these islands and many others. &lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
