<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Las Casas’ account of the atrocities of the Spanish in the New World fed directly into broader European prejudices concerning the greed and rapacity of both the new imperialists and of the Catholic Church whom they represented. After all, the Catholic Church’s wealth was one of the central grievances behind the Reformation. &lt;br />&lt;br />Although a devout, Catholic Las Casas here describes explicitly how greed has contributed to Spanish crimes in their American colonies. That he has specified a greed for gold is notable. It was the extraction of material wealth, the principle of mercantilism, that played a crucial motivating factor in Spanish imperial expansion into the Americas.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
