<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Crafted with an eye on its rhetorical impact, Las Casas’ descriptions of the Natives and of the Spanish are notable for their stark contrast. As seen above, the natives are frequently idyllic and pacific people. By contrast, here describing the Spanish at work on the island of Hispaniola (the Greater Antilles, i.e. the Dominican Republic / Haiti), his descriptions come alive with scenes of almost unimaginable cruelty. He is again keen to stress that these are crimes committed by Christians, designed to shock his contemporary readers into action.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>
&lt;p style="-qt-paragraph-type:empty; margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px; font-family:'.SF NS Text';">&lt;br />&lt;/p>
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Such graphic descriptions fed into the broader European imagination and contributed to the so-called Black Legend. As competition between European states spilled over into brutal warfare in the 16th and 17th centuries, descriptions such as those of Las Casas here inspired horrific artworks, usually in Protestant states, produced to validate their continued struggles against the Catholic Spanish. A notable example is the etchings of Theodor de Bry, a Flemmish artist forced to flee the Netherlands during the repressions of the Spanish Inquisition in the late 16th century. His subsequent work was distinctly anti-Spanish and anti-Catholic in nature, and was frequently inspired by writings such as Las Casas’.&lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
