<text>&lt;!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.0//EN" "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-html40/strict.dtd">
&lt;html>&lt;head>&lt;meta name="qrichtext" content="1" />&lt;style type="text/css">
p, li { white-space: pre-wrap; }
&lt;/style>&lt;/head>&lt;body style=" font-family:'.AppleSystemUIFont'; font-size:13pt; font-weight:400; font-style:normal;">
&lt;p style=" margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:0px; margin-left:0px; margin-right:0px; -qt-block-indent:0; text-indent:0px;">&lt;span style=" font-family:'.SF NS Text';">Towards the end of his treatise, Las Casas reaffirms that his work is directed to the Spanish Crown, whom ostensibly controlled the colonies (the reality was frequently that in this early modern empire, the vast distances between the colony and the central authority made effective control nigh impossible. Las Casas also refers to the New Laws of 1542, which abolished the slavery of native Americans in the Spanish colonies. Although crimes continued to be committed, and the natives continued to be exploited, maltreated, and brutalized, the promulgation of such laws does indicate that there were movements within Spanish society to change their approach to Empire. &lt;/span>&lt;/p>&lt;/body>&lt;/html></text>
